System Overview & Agent Reasoning

The proposed AI agent is built on a multi-step agentic loop powered by a large language model (GPT-4 / Gemini 1.5
Pro) orchestrated through LangChain / LangGraph. When a user sends a message on the shopping platform, it first
passes through an Input Processor and Validator module that performs NLP tokenisation, intent extraction,
input-length checks, XSS sanitisation, and rate-limit enforcement. Clean input is forwarded to the LLM Reasoning
Engine, which maintains conversational memory (short-term via ConversationBufferMemory and long-term via a
Redis-backed store) and invokes registered tools using a ReAct (Reason + Act) prompting strategy. The agent first
generates a chain-of-thought plan, decides which tool or backend to call, executes the tool, observes the result, and
iterates until it has enough information to produce a final answer. This loop is managed by the LangGraph state
machine, which tracks each agent step and enforces maximum-iteration guards to prevent infinite loops.
The Intent Classifier (a fine-tuned BERT / zero-shot classification head) categorises every query into one of three
buckets: Informational (policy, shipping, returns), Operational (live order status, account details, refund initiation), or
Escalation (complaints, sensitive issues, repeated failures). This classification drives the routing decision – ensuring
each query touches only the relevant backend, reducing latency and protecting sensitive APIs from unnecessary calls


Backend Service Interaction & Response Synthesis

For Informational queries, the agent invokes the RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) pipeline: the query is
embedded using OpenAI text-embedding-3-small, searched against a FAISS vector store containing indexed policy
documents, FAQs, and delivery SLAs, and the top-k chunks are injected into the LLM prompt as context. For
Operational queries, the agent first validates the provided Order ID (regex format check) and verifies the user's auth
token via the Auth Service. Only after successful validation does it call the Order Service (REST API to
order-management DB), Account Service (customer profile/CRM), or Payment Service (refund/transaction history) –
each exposed as a LangChain Tool. All retrieved data flows into the Response Aggregator, which ranks and merges
partial results, then passes them to the Output Formatter to produce a structured JSON payload (rendered as a rich
card or plain text in the UI). For Escalation, the Escalation Engine evaluates rule-based triggers (e.g., 3+ failed order
lookups, negative sentiment score below threshold via a fine-tuned DistilBERT sentiment model) and, when triggered,
hands off to a human agent queue via a Zendesk / Freshdesk webhook, attaching the full conversation transcript for
context.
